 <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

 <!-- Answer-first TL;DR -->
 <aside class="mb-10 rounded-2xl border border-gold-500/30 bg-navy-900/60 p-7">
 <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">Quick Answer</p>
 <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-white sm:text-xl">Embroidery pricing on a single shirt is driven by 5 factors: stitch count (logo complexity), garment cost, setup or digitizing fee, decoration complexity (placements, thread colors), and quantity. Industry rule of thumb is about $1 per 1,000 stitches once digitizing is done, plus the cost of the shirt itself, plus a one-time digitizing fee for new logos.</p>
 </aside>

 <h2 id="stitch-count" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">1. Stitch Count Drives Most of the Cost</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Embroidery is priced by the stitch, not the inch. A standard left-chest logo runs 5,000–8,000 stitches; a back logo can run 25,000–40,000. The shop charges for thread consumption and machine time, both of which scale with stitch count.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">A simple bold logo (text + outline) might be 4,000 stitches. A detailed logo with gradients and fills can hit 12,000+ at the same physical size. Same chest position, very different cost. Simplifying a logo for embroidery — or having a "stitch-optimized" version digitized — is the single biggest lever for bringing per-piece costs down.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">For deep background on what makes a logo embroider well vs. badly, see <a href="/blog/logo-digitizing-101-embroidery/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">logo digitizing 101</a>.</p>

 <h2 id="garment" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">2. The Garment Itself</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">A blank shirt's wholesale cost varies wildly. A basic 5.5 oz t-shirt might wholesale at $3–5; a Carhartt Force performance polo runs $25–35; a Bulwark FR shirt runs $60–90. Industry pricing typically marks blank cost up modestly, but the wholesale cost of the garment is the floor — there's no way to embroider a $90 FR shirt at $20 retail.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">For trade-vertical specs (which garment fits which use case), see our industry pages — <a href="/industries/plumbing-hvac-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">plumbing &amp; HVAC</a>, <a href="/industries/electrical-contractors-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">electrical contractors</a>, and others list the standard garment SKUs by trade.</p>

 <h2 id="setup" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">3. Setup &amp; Digitizing Fees (One-Time)</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200"><strong>Digitizing</strong> converts your logo into a stitch file the embroidery machine can read. It's typically $30–80 per logo, charged once. Reorders use the same file at no additional charge.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200"><strong>Setup</strong> covers thread color matching, hooping, and machine prep. Some shops charge a setup fee per order ($15–35); others bundle it into per-piece pricing on volume runs.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Once digitizing is done, the file lives on. We keep customer logo files indefinitely so reorders never re-pay for digitizing.</p>

 <h2 id="complexity" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">4. Decoration Complexity</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">A single left-chest logo is the simplest run. Adding a name on the right chest doubles the operations per shirt. Adding a sleeve hit triples it. Each placement requires re-hooping the garment and a separate machine pass. Multi-placement shirts cost meaningfully more per piece than single-placement.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Thread color count matters less than people expect — modern multi-needle machines handle 12+ thread colors without significant added cost. The exception is metallic or specialty threads, which can run 2–3x the cost of standard polyester.</p>

 <h2 id="quantity" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">5. Quantity</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Volume discounts are real but smaller than people expect on embroidery. Unlike screen printing — where the per-piece cost falls dramatically with quantity because most cost is in setup — embroidery cost is mostly in machine time, which scales linearly with quantity. A 100-piece run might be 10–15% cheaper per piece than a 24-piece run; a 500-piece run might be 20–25% cheaper.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">For comparison on the screen-printing side, see <a href="/blog/screen-printing-vs-embroidery-construction/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">screen printing vs. embroidery</a>.</p>

 <h2 id="how-long" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">How Long Does It Take to Embroider 1,000 Stitches?</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Standard commercial multi-needle embroidery machines run 600–1,000 stitches per minute, depending on the design and the machine. So 1,000 stitches takes roughly 1–2 minutes of machine time per piece. A typical left-chest logo (5,000–8,000 stitches) takes 5–12 minutes per shirt of pure machine time, plus hooping and unhooping.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Production capacity at a commercial embroidery shop is measured in pieces per hour, not minutes per shirt. A 6-head machine running an 8,000-stitch logo can produce roughly 30–45 finished shirts per hour. That's why bulk orders ship in days, not weeks.</p>

 <h2 id="getting-quote" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Getting an Accurate Quote</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Three things to send when you're getting an embroidery quote:</p>
 <ol class="mb-6 list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
 <li><strong>Your logo</strong> in vector format (.ai, .eps, .pdf) if possible. JPG/PNG works but may require redrawing.</li>
 <li><strong>The garment</strong> — specific SKU if you know it, otherwise a description (polo, work shirt, hi-vis tee).</li>
 <li><strong>Quantity and placements</strong> — how many shirts, and where the logo goes (left chest, back, sleeve).</li>
 </ol>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">For broader buyer education on what to ask for, the <a href="https://www.promoproducts.com/" rel="noopener" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">Promotional Products Association International</a> has industry primers worth reading.</p>

 <div class="mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-gold-500/40 bg-gold-500/5 p-7 sm:p-9">
 <h2 class="mb-3 font-heading text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white">Get an embroidery quote in Las Vegas</h2>
 <p class="mb-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Bighorn Threads runs commercial embroidery for Vegas contractors, trades, and service businesses. Send your logo and quantity — we'll quote per piece including digitizing if it's a new logo.</p>
 <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex min-h-[48px] items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-gold-500 px-7 py-3 text-base font-bold text-navy-950 transition-all hover:bg-gold-400">Get a Quote →</a>
 </div>
 </div>
 </article>
